This year promises too be a great year for a reunion of Marines I served with in Vietnam. We plan to have our second reunion in late May, 1998 while the traveling wall is in Riverside. <br><br>
I started this thread for us to share stories of joys and comforts we find this year, in making contact with our past while reaching out toward our furture.<br><br>
The following story is of another type of HOMECOMING: <br><br>
Laos officials turn over remains purported to be of Vietnam MIA<br><br>
By David E. Hendrix<br>
The Press-Enterprise<br><br>
Lost and found. Lost and found.<br><br>
Albro Lundy III and his family have had more than enough of the emotional ride that started when his father was reported missing in action during the Vietnam War.<br><br>
The newest chapter for the Lundy family involves a box of bones and the military identity records that Laotian officials turned over this week to U.S. officials. The remnants of life and service are purported to belong to Albro Lundy Jr., an Air Force pilot whose plane was shot down over Laos during the Vietnam War.<br><br>
The remains handed over Tuesday mark the first time since the war that Laos unilaterally has provided such material without protracted negotiations, an act for which Lundy III expresses gratitude -- if they are his dad's bones.<br><br>
But his father's name and likeness have flashed before the world before and the experience has left the Redondo Beach attorney skeptical. His father was one of three missing U.S. pilots, including the son of a San Bernardino County woman, who allegedly were photographed in 1990 and whose picture was circulated worldwide in 1991.<br><br>
The photo, ultimately branded a fraud by U.S. government analysts, prompted the Senate to create a special committee that spent 1992 investigating whether American POWs were left behind when the Vietnam War ended. The select committee concluded that some probably were left behind but no positive proof existed.<br><br>
&quot;Right now, I don't know if he (father) is alive, but the credibility of these remains is high . . . because they are returning with all of these identifiers,&quot; Lundy said Thursday. The Laotians turned over dog tags, a military ID card and a piece of fabric bearing a personalized identification number.<br><br>
&quot;But we're going to have independent forensic analysis. We're not going to let them bury the bones of some pig and call it Albro Lundy Jr.&quot;<br><br>
Lundy was 10 when his father left for Southeast Asia in 1970. He and his five siblings lost their dad when his plane was shot down over Laos that Christmas Eve. For the next 21 years, the Lundy family got little information about the incident.<br><br>
In late 1990, the Lundys thought they might have found their missing father and Johanna Lundy of Palos Verdes her missing husband. A photo of three men -- purported to be Lundy Jr., Air Force Col. John Robertson and Navy Lt. Larry Stevens -- was released to their families. They had the picture analyzed and concluded it was of their missing loved ones. But the government disagreed.<br><br>
Stevens is the son of Gladys Fleckenstein of Big Bear. She said Thursday that she hoped for the Lundys' sake that the remains and identification were not another false lead. She said she believes her son is alive and she has received reports that he was seen as recently as last year.<br><br>
Barbara Robertson of Santa Ana has had problems with alleged remains in recent years. Her husband's plane was shot down over Vietnam in 1966.<br><br>
&quot;Rock and animal bones were returned through official channels about a year after the photo and called his remains but weren't,&quot; Robertson said. &quot;His helmet reportedly was found but it wasn't.<br><br>
&quot;I don't think people know how badly that hurts. We're not people with our heads buried in the sand. We just want the truth.&quot;<br><br>
In 1994, Lundy and a younger brother, William, independently found their father's crash site in Laos and returned with part of the A-1E's canopy. In 1995, Lundy said, a Laotian official offered William the father's identity cards for &quot;a substantial amount of money.&quot; The offer was declined and his father's trail grew cold.<br><br>
Lundy said the family will accept his father's death if it is proved, but he had to remain skeptical of official U.S. efforts because of experience.<br><br>
&quot;We would appreciate very much the ability to say goodbye and I would be glad to live my life without thinking daily, `Is my dad alive in some prison hole in a jungle and am I doing everything I can to bring him home?' &quot;<br><br>
Published 10/31/1997, from the Press Enterprise<br><br>
Cook Barela<br>

